Unlike RO, which constructs the ambitious set directly based on the samples, DRO constructs the ambitious set based on the possible distribution of the samples. Since the actual distribution of the variables is not likely to deviate significantly from the distribution of the samples, the actual distribution can be considered to be included as long as the constraints of the distribution information are reasonable. Thus, only the worst possible distribution situation needs to be found to ensure the result is a lower bound for the performance under the actual sample distribution. By incorporating the distribution information of the samples, the redundant space of the ambitious set can be effectively reduced, thereby decreasing the conservativeness of the RO. The ambitious set of DRO is formulated as:26ψ=pkpk≥0∑k=1Kpk=1∑k=1Kpk-pk0≤γ1maxpk-pk0≤γ∞,k=1,2,…,K.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
